One of my "to dos" from our on-going discussion was to look up examples where we "wait until initialized" by looking at bundle (plugin) states. I believe this is prefered over synchronizing on the plugin/bundle itself. 


In this example from StructuredModelManger.gerModelManger(), we just spin until our bundle is active, if we know we "need" that plugin to accomplish much. We implemented this in previous versions when we found some threads (maybe even from resource change events!) were tying to do stuff with the model manager, before the plugin/bundle was completely active ... or, they were trying to do stuff on shutdown, after this particular plugin had already been deactivated). 

Not sure this method is perfect, but it is (was) similar to others in the Eclipse platform, and has had long-ago (old) review by John A. 


/**
 * Provides access to the instance of IModelManager. Returns null if model
 * manager can not be created or is not valid (such as, when workbench is
 * shutting down).
 *
 * @return IModelManager - returns the one model manager for structured
 *         model
 */
public static IModelManager getModelManager() {
        boolean isReady = false;
        IModelManager modelManager = null;
        while (!isReady) {
                Bundle localBundle = Platform.getBundle(SSECorePlugin.ID);
                int state = localBundle.getState();
                if (state == Bundle.ACTIVE) {
                        isReady = true;
                        // getInstance is a synchronized static method.
                        modelManager = ModelManagerImpl.getInstance();
                }
                else if (state == Bundle.STARTING) {
                        try {
                                Thread.sleep(100);
                        }
                        catch (InterruptedException e) {
                                // ignore, just loop again
                        }
                }
                else if (state == Bundle.STOPPING || state == Bundle.UNINSTALLED) {
                        isReady = true;
                        modelManager = null;
                }
                else {
                        // not sure about other states, 'resolved', 'installed'
                        isReady = true;
                        modelManager = null;
                }
        }
        return modelManager;
}


Hope this helps.
